Purpose-built databases: the rest of the zoo.

A handful of databases exist because both relational and DynamoDB are the wrong shapes for specific workloads. Each one is a one-liner away from being unfit for everything else, and the value is in recognising the cue and jumping to the service.

DocumentDB is a MongoDB-compatible document store, with the same Aurora-style storage underneath: six copies across three availability zones, auto-growing to a hundred twenty-eight terabytes, and up to fifteen read replicas. Use it for MongoDB workloads you're migrating, or catalog data with variable structure. The cue is MongoDB or document database. Neptune is a fully managed graph database; it models data as nodes and edges and runs traversal queries via Gremlin, openCypher, or SPARQL. It fits highly connected data: social graphs, fraud detection through link analysis, recommendation engines, and knowledge graphs. The cue is graph, social network, fraud, friend-of-friend, or interconnected. Keyspaces is serverless Cassandra-compatible; the cue is Cassandra or C-Q-L. Timestream is purpose-built for time-series; the cue is I-o-T, sensors, or metrics over time. MemoryDB is Redis as a durable primary store, not just a cache but a multi-A-Z durable database; the cue is Redis as the system of record. And Q-L-D-B is an immutable, cryptographically verifiable ledger, a centralised audit trail; the cue is a tamper-proof audit log or verifiable history. For a decentralised, multi-party ledger instead, that's Managed Blockchain.

The pattern is cue-to-service, not service-to-capability. You don't learn every feature; you learn the one phrase in a scenario that jumps you to the right service.
